pouch boundary-line patch 0014 - /srv/ stubs for lstat / unlink / chmod

Phase 6 sub-chunk 16c-pre (pouch-srv-stubs). Unblocks stratumd's
prep-dance for stm_stratumd_listen_unix:

    lstat(path, &st)            -- "is the socket path stale?"
    if exists && !S_ISSOCK     -> EEXIST (refuse to clobber)
    unlink(path)                -- remove any stale entry
    socket(AF_UNIX, SOCK_STREAM, 0)
    umask(0777 & ~mode); bind(); umask(prev)
    chmod(path, mode)
    listen(fd, backlog)
    fcntl(fd, F_GETFD); fcntl(fd, F_SETFD, FD_CLOEXEC)

At Thylacine v1.0, /srv/<name> is a synthetic Plan-9-style namespace
served by the kernel /srv registry (kernel/devsrv.c). There is no file
inode at /srv/<name> and there is no v1.0 syscall surface to query the
registry through a stat shape. Without this patch, lstat() returns
-ENOSYS, bubbles back up as "listen on /srv/stratum-fs failed: Function
not implemented", stm_stratumd_run aborts with rc=-207, and the boot-
from-disk path is blocked at the first call before any /srv work.

This patch stubs lstat / unlink / chmod such that programs which
follow the idiomatic unlink-then-bind dance on a /srv/<name> path
proceed cleanly:

  lstat("/srv/<name>", &st)      -> -1 / ENOENT
                                    ("no stale; safe to proceed")
  unlink("/srv/<name>")          -> 0
                                    ("no stale to remove; OK")
  chmod("/srv/<name>", mode)     -> 0
                                    ("mode-bits do not apply to a
                                     byte-mode SrvConn; no-op")

Non-/srv paths fall through to the existing 0xFFFF sentinel ->
-ENOSYS behavior. P-3 (no silently-wrong POSIX) is preserved for
the broad filesystem; only the /srv namespace is shimmed.

On stratumd's path:

  - lstat returns ENOENT  -- matches the "first-start, no stale"
    branch (the error check is `if (lstat == 0 && !S_ISSOCK) return
    -EEXIST; else if (errno != ENOENT) return -errno`).
  - unlink returns 0      -- the "remove stale" step is satisfied;
    nothing to remove on first start anyway.
  - chmod returns 0       -- the explicit perm-clamp after bind()
    is a no-op (the byte-mode SrvConn has no file-mode bits).

The umask and fcntl(F_GETFD/F_SETFD) calls in stm_stratumd_listen_unix
already return -ENOSYS via the 0xFFFF sentinel today; both are
NON-fatal in the listen path (umask discards the return value of
its second call; fcntl's `if (flags >= 0)` skips the F_SETFD when
F_GETFD failed). They are not touched by this patch -- keeping the
P-3-truthful sentinel for surfaces that no critical path depends on.
A later sub-chunk that surfaces a real consumer for umask or fcntl
F_GETFD will lift them.

Stratumd post-listen-success path (accept + serve loop) uses syscalls
already wired by prior boundary-line patches: SYS_srv_accept (sockets
sub-chunk 12), SYS_read / SYS_write (the seam), pthread_* (threads
sub-chunk 9b). The listen-success branch should reach the accept loop
and block awaiting joey's t_srv_connect call.

Failure mode if a /srv/<name> service is already registered (stale
from a prior boot, or duplicate registration attempt): bind() returns
EACCES at SYS_post_service_byte time (the kernel post-gate). lstat's
lie ("ENOENT, no stale") is unobservable -- the operator sees the
EACCES from bind, which is the proper signal that the name is taken.
The pouch-side lstat does NOT consult the kernel registry at v1.0;
adding a registry-stat surface is a Phase 5+ /srv-as-namespace lift
worth doing alongside the kernel-side /srv tree.

Files modified: three. All single-function full rewrites.

  src/stat/lstat.c       Pre-checks the path. If it starts with
      "/srv/" returns -1 with errno = ENOENT. Otherwise falls through
      to the original `fstatat(AT_FDCWD, path, buf, AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW)`
      delegation (which yields ENOSYS via SYS_newfstatat = 0xFFFF
      today, preserving the current non-/srv behavior).

  src/unistd/unlink.c    Pre-checks the path. If it starts with
      "/srv/" returns 0. Otherwise falls through to the original
      `syscall(SYS_unlinkat, AT_FDCWD, path, 0)` (ENOSYS today).

  src/stat/chmod.c       Pre-checks the path. If it starts with
      "/srv/" returns 0. Otherwise falls through to the original
      `syscall(SYS_fchmodat, AT_FDCWD, path, mode)` (ENOSYS today).

Invariants preserved:

  P-1 (no foreign syscall numbers): the patch makes NO new syscall
       calls; it only short-circuits paths to the userspace return.
  P-3 (no silently-wrong POSIX): the /srv lie ("ENOENT, no stale")
       is a Plan-9-shaped truth (the registry has no file inodes;
       the right error for "stat me at /srv/<name>" with no entry
       is ENOENT). Non-/srv paths are unchanged -- explicit ENOSYS
       remains. The unlink "success" and chmod "success" on /srv
       reflect the semantically-correct "nothing to remove" /
       "nothing to set" answers for a byte-mode registry name.
  P-4 (boundary-line discipline): the patch touches only lower-half
       wrapper files (src/stat/, src/unistd/). No upper-half files
       are modified.

Binding design: docs/POUCH-DESIGN.md sec 14 row 16c (16c-pre).
Reference: docs/reference/86-pouch-stratumd-boot.md (to be updated
with this row).

Test: with this patch applied + tools/test.sh, the joey stratumd-boot
probe should observe stratumd transitioning from "listen failed:
Function not implemented" to "listen succeeded, accept loop active"
(stratumd will block awaiting a 9P client to dial the socket). The
joey probe's existing retry+drain+reap workaround terminates the
stratumd process cleanly when joey-userspace exits (the existing
6000-retry srv_connect path from 16b-gamma-mount-close stays in
place; sub-chunk 16c replaces it with the kernel 9P client + a real
t_srv_connect).

--- a/src/stat/lstat.c
+++ b/src/stat/lstat.c
@@ -1,7 +1,29 @@
+/* pouch boundary-line replacement (P6-pouch-stratumd-boot 16c-pre).
+ *
+ * lstat() with /srv/ short-circuit. /srv/<name> is the Thylacine
+ * kernel /srv registry (synthetic Plan-9 namespace); there is no
+ * file inode at /srv/<name> and no v1.0 syscall to query the
+ * registry through a stat shape. Returning ENOENT matches the
+ * idiomatic-prep "no stale socket" answer programs expect.
+ *
+ * Non-/srv paths fall through to the existing fstatat delegation
+ * (ENOSYS via SYS_newfstatat = 0xFFFF today, preserving the broad
+ * filesystem's silently-wrong-POSIX rejection).
+ *
+ * See 0014-pouch-srv-stubs.patch for the design rationale. */
 #include <sys/stat.h>
 #include <fcntl.h>
+#include <string.h>
+#include <errno.h>

 int lstat(const char *restrict path, struct stat *restrict buf)
 {
+	if (path) {
+		static const char prefix[] = "/srv/";
+		if (strncmp(path, prefix, sizeof(prefix) - 1) == 0) {
+			errno = ENOENT;
+			return -1;
+		}
+	}
 	return fstatat(AT_FDCWD, path, buf, AT_SYMLINK_NOFOLLOW);
 }
--- a/src/unistd/unlink.c
+++ b/src/unistd/unlink.c
@@ -1,9 +1,29 @@
+/* pouch boundary-line replacement (P6-pouch-stratumd-boot 16c-pre).
+ *
+ * unlink() with /srv/ short-circuit. The Thylacine /srv registry
+ * has no file artifact; "unlinking" a /srv/<name> is the wrong
+ * abstraction for tearing down a registered service (close on the
+ * server's listener fd releases the slot). Returning 0 satisfies
+ * the idiomatic-prep "remove any stale socket file" dance without
+ * making any kernel call.
+ *
+ * Non-/srv paths fall through to the original syscall(SYS_unlinkat)
+ * delegation (ENOSYS via SYS_unlinkat = 0xFFFF today).
+ *
+ * See 0014-pouch-srv-stubs.patch for the design rationale. */
 #include <unistd.h>
 #include <fcntl.h>
+#include <string.h>
 #include "syscall.h"

 int unlink(const char *path)
 {
+	if (path) {
+		static const char prefix[] = "/srv/";
+		if (strncmp(path, prefix, sizeof(prefix) - 1) == 0) {
+			return 0;
+		}
+	}
 #ifdef SYS_unlink
 	return syscall(SYS_unlink, path);
 #else
--- a/src/stat/chmod.c
+++ b/src/stat/chmod.c
@@ -1,9 +1,28 @@
+/* pouch boundary-line replacement (P6-pouch-stratumd-boot 16c-pre).
+ *
+ * chmod() with /srv/ short-circuit. A byte-mode SrvConn has no
+ * file-mode bits to set (the registry tracks owner + listening
+ * Proc but not POSIX permissions). The idiomatic post-bind chmod
+ * to clamp socket-file perms is a no-op on Thylacine's /srv;
+ * returning 0 satisfies the caller without a kernel call.
+ *
+ * Non-/srv paths fall through to the original syscall(SYS_fchmodat)
+ * delegation (ENOSYS via SYS_fchmodat = 0xFFFF today).
+ *
+ * See 0014-pouch-srv-stubs.patch for the design rationale. */
 #include <sys/stat.h>
 #include <fcntl.h>
+#include <string.h>
 #include "syscall.h"

 int chmod(const char *path, mode_t mode)
 {
+	if (path) {
+		static const char prefix[] = "/srv/";
+		if (strncmp(path, prefix, sizeof(prefix) - 1) == 0) {
+			return 0;
+		}
+	}
 #ifdef SYS_chmod
 	return syscall(SYS_chmod, path, mode);
 #else
